  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I learn spoken English?",
  "response": "Learning spoken English involves a combination of listening, speaking, and practicing regularly. Here are some steps you can follow to improve your spoken English:\n\n### 1. **Immerse Yourself in the Language**\n   - **Watch English Media**: Watch movies, TV shows, and YouTube videos in English. Start with subtitles and gradually move to watching without them.\n   - **Listen to English Music and Podcasts**: This can help you get used to different accents and improve your listening skills.\n\n### 2. **Practice Speaking**\n   - **Talk to Native Speakers**: If possible, find language exchange partners or join a conversation group.\n   - **Use Language Learning Apps**: Apps like Duolingo, Babbel, and HelloTalk can connect you with native speakers for practice.\n   - **Record Yourself**: Record your speech and listen to it to identify areas for improvement.\n\n### 3. **Improve Your Pronunciation**\n   - **Use Pronunciation Guides**: Websites like Forvo and apps like ELSA Speak can help you with pronunciation.\n   - **Practice Phonetics**: Learn the phonetic alphabet to understand how sounds are made.\n\n### 4. **Build Your Vocabulary**\n   - **Read English Books, Articles, and Websites**: This will expose you to new words and phrases.\n   - **Use Flashcards**: Apps like Anki and Quizlet can help you memorize new vocabulary.\n\n### 5. **Focus on Grammar**\n   - **Study Grammar Rules**: Use textbooks or online resources like Grammarly to understand grammar better.\n   - **Practice Writing**: Writing essays or journal entries can help solidify your understanding of grammar rules.\n\n### 6. **Engage in Conversation Practice**\n   - **Join Language Meetups**: Look for local or online groups where you can practice speaking.\n   - **Role-play Common Scenarios**: Practice common situations like ordering food, asking for directions, or making small talk.\n\n### 7. **Use Technology**\n   - **Speech-to-Text Software**: Tools like Google's speech-to-text can help you see how accurately you're speaking.\n   - **Virtual Reality (VR)**: Some VR platforms offer immersive language learning experiences.\n\n### 8. **Set Realistic Goals**\n   - **Short-term Goals**: Aim to learn a certain number of new words each week or have a conversation for a set amount of time.\n   - **Long-term Goals**: Set milestones like being able to watch a movie without subtitles or having a fluent conversation with a native speaker.\n\n### 9. **Be Consistent and Patient**\n   - **Daily Practice**: Spend some time each day practicing, even if it's just 15-30 minutes.\n   - **Stay Motivated**: Celebrate your progress and don't get discouraged by setbacks.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n- **Use English in Your Daily Life**: Try to think in English, label objects in your home with their English names, and even talk to yourself in English.\n- **Get Feedback**: Ask for feedback from teachers, tutors, or native speakers to identify areas for improvement.\n\nBy following these steps and staying committed, you'll gradually improve your spoken English skills.",
